n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>There are many ways to prove Heron's formula, for example using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigonometry">trig=
onometry</a> as below, or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ince=
nter" title=3D"Incenter">incenter</a> and one <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Excircle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Excircle">excircle</a>=
 of the triangle,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron%27s_formula#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or as a=
 special case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Gua%27s_theore=
m" title=3D"De Gua's theorem">De Gua's theorem</a> (for the particular case=
 of acute triangles),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron%27s_formula#cite_note-9"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or =
as a special case of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagupta%2=
7s_formula" title=3D"Brahmagupta's formula">Brahmagupta's formula</a> (for =
the case of a degenerate cyclic quadrilateral).
</p>
