riangle</a>, a line segment with zero area. In this case, the semiperimeter=
 will equal the longest side, causing Heron's formula to equal zero.
</p><p>If one of three given lengths is greater than the sum of the other t=
wo, then they violate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle=
_inequality" title=3D"Triangle inequality">triangle inequality</a> and do n=
ot describe the sides of a Euclidean triangle. In this case, Heron's formul=
a gives an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_number" title=
=3D"Imaginary number">imaginary</a> result. For example if <span class=3D"n=
owrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle a=3D3}">
